english:
  title: Letter on the Same Matter
  author: Yu Seung-dan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly offer this missive. As early winter's first chill settles upon the land, I trust Your Majesty enjoys robust health and ten thousand blessings. On this day in the tenth month, your envoys Gye-do and Bul-hap have brought word, and learning of Your Majesty's continued wellness fills me with boundless joy.

    Regarding the matter of presenting tribute gifts, when your messenger Tao-hu arrived in the eighth month with Your Majesty's letter, we hastily assembled local goods—silks of various hues, dyed and fulled to perfection—along with otter pelts, cotton, hemp cloth, paper, and ink, all chosen from our finest stocks. Yet our kingdom's land is poor and our people impoverished; our yearly revenues are meager. Thus the burden of preparation weighs heavily. Nevertheless, following precedent, we have made ready these offerings, which depart with your same messenger.

    As for the writing brushes requested, they are traditionally made from yellow rat hair. Yet such creatures dwell not in our realm, and thus we cannot fulfill this need.

    Regarding the establishment of an inn—this matter weighs upon our own hearts as essential. Though your words prompted us, we harbored such intentions already. What has stayed our hand is this: each year when your envoys arrive, guards accompany them in great numbers. They linger long within our borders, and through each village and station they pass, disturbance ripples outward. Our people grow reluctant to dwell along the roads, and thus the work remains unfinished.

    Now fortune smiles upon the border between our nations—no difficulties block the way. Even without guards, travel may proceed smoothly. Should guards prove necessary, let them remain upon your side of the boundary at Dong-jin, not setting foot upon our soil. We ask only that you give advance notice of your envoys' crossing, that our own people might receive and escort them properly. Thus both realms find ease.

    Yet I must speak plainly: the protocols between our kingdoms require fixed measure. Yearly missions have long been custom. Now each delegation divides into two successive visits, and separate envoys come besides. Thus three times in a single year, your traffic arrives. Without firm limits, this will multiply year upon year. Our people grow weary, our treasury thins, and we fear our strength may soon falter beneath the burden.

    I earnestly beseech you: let us return to the numbers and ceremonies established in the first month of the Ki-myo year. One mission yearly, coming and going in proper order, serves both realms far better. I beg your understanding and compassion in this matter.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Ki-myo year (己卯年) refers to 1519, when diplomatic protocols between the two nations were formally established.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'yellow rat hair' (黃鼠毛) likely refers to a rare material prized for fine brushes, unavailable in the Korean kingdom.
  - key: ''
    value: Dong-jin (東眞) appears to be a border region where the neighboring kingdom's guards were stationed.
